Case Study: Phishing

Phishing is a type of online fraud in which people are tricked into giving their personal information such as passwords, bank details, or OTPs. This usually happens through fake emails, messages, or websites that look similar to real ones.

For example, a student may receive a message claiming to be from their bank or a popular app, saying that their account will be blocked or there is some urgent issue. The message includes a link which looks genuine. When the student clicks on the link, it opens a fake website that looks exactly like the original one. If the student enters their login details or OTP, the information goes to the scammer.

Phishing mainly targets people who are not aware of such scams or who trust messages without checking properly. Students are also common targets because they frequently use online payments, UPI apps, and social media.

The consequences of phishing can be serious. A person may lose money from their bank account, their social media accounts can get hacked, or their personal information can be misused. In some cases, it can also lead to identity theft.

This case shows that people should always be careful while clicking on links and never share sensitive information without verifying the source.Case Study: Phishing

